pullRequest.body:
Define partial equivalences between structures. A partial equivalence between structures `M` and `N` is a subobject of `M` and a subobject of `N` along with an equivalence between. This is useful to build an actual equivalence between `M` and `N`.

---

This is part of preparations toward #9967.

- [x] depends on: #11174
- [x] depends on: #15408

I just merged master into this because there was a merge conflict - I'll also take this opportunity to say that I approve this content.

@YaelDillies , this version is correct. The version you are thinking of differs only in the presence of an equivalence/isomorphism between the whole structures that restricts to the equivalence between substructures. We want to use partial isomorphisms to _construct_ such an isomorphism, without the assumption that one exists.

I've decided to rename them `PartialEquiv`, though, matching partial bijections defined elsewhere.
Ah okay, this name change clears it up! I was expecting that the global equivalence already existed and you cared about its restrictions.

I've moved the real new content to a new file and its own namespace. The later PRs in this sequence also have a lot of results about the type of finitely-generated partial equivalences, which I think should also go in that file.

I'm having trouble understanding your definition of subequivalence on a conceptual level. 

A subequivalence according to your PR takes in a language `L`, two `L`-structures `M` and `N` and consists of a `L`-substructure of `M`, a `L`-substructure of `N`, an equivalence between those substructures.

I would instead have expected it to take in a language `L`, two `L`-structures `M` and `N`, an equivalence between `M` and `N` and consist of a `L`-substructure of `M` and a `L`-substructure of `N` that are equivalent under the equivalence between `M` and `N`,

Am I thinking about subequivalences wrong?

```suggestion
structure SubEquivalence where
```

You have the space in other places
```suggestion
  /-- The substructure which is the domain of the equivalence. -/
  sub_dom : L.Substructure M
  /-- The substructure which is the codomain of the equivalence. -/
  sub_cod : L.Substructure N
  /-- The equivalence between the two subdomains. -/
```
For clarity, almost all files have the spaces here. I don't particularly mind either way, but now this PR is making this file stand out
Looks you went for restoring the spaces but only restored the leading ones, not the trailing ones?

Oops - another find and replace mistake.
I think I've fixed that now, but I think I should make a separate PR to go and clean up all the whitespace in the model theory files, since that isn't the point of this PR, and I see some other whitespace issues in my files.

```suggestion
  the type of equivalences between substructures of `M` and `N`.
```
I believe the vscode highlighting shows you that not indenting is considered incorrect by markdown. I also believe that docgen doesn't care and will do what you meant, but might as well comply ðŸ¤·
Apologies if this is obvious, but what is the `â‚š` in the notation standing for? "partial"?

Yes - I'm thinking that these should be renamed `PartialEquiv`, and possibly other bits of nomenclature should be changed to match https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/PartialEquiv.html

```suggestion
theorem le_def (f g : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) : f â‰¤ g â†” âˆƒ h : f.sub_dom â‰¤ g.sub_dom,
```

```suggestion
/--Maps to the symmetric partial equivalence.-/
```

```suggestion
theorem le_source {f g : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N} : f â‰¤ g â†’ f.source â‰¤ g.source := fun âŸ¨le, _âŸ© â†¦ le
```
or rename the field of `PartialEquiv` to `dom`

~~This could be stated with `Monotone` with name `dom_mono`. Mind doing that?~~ I see it's stated further down

But please also keep the existing lemma stated with `â‰¤` under the name `dom_le_dom` (it's important to have `dom` on both sides for clarity. Sometimes a function appears only on one side, that usually happens when there is a Galois connection hanging about) and tag it with `@[gcongr]`.

```suggestion
protected theorem le_refl (f : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) : f â‰¤ f := âŸ¨le_rfl, rflâŸ©
```
or even
```suggestion
private theorem le_refl (f : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) : f â‰¤ f := âŸ¨le_rfl, rflâŸ©
```
actually since it's superseded by the `PartialOrder (M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N)` instance

Same here and above
```suggestion
private theorem le_antisymm (f g : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) (le_fg : f â‰¤ g) (le_gf : g â‰¤ f) : f = g := by
```

Can you also separately provide
```
@[gcongr] lemma symm_le_symm {h : f â‰¤ g) : f.symm â‰¤ g.symm
```

```suggestion
theorem symm_le_iff {f : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N} {g : N â‰ƒâ‚š[L] M} : f.symm â‰¤ g â†” f â‰¤ g.symm :=
```
since it's an iff

```suggestion
noncomputable def domRestrict (f : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) {A : L.Substructure M} (h : A â‰¤ f.source) :
```

```suggestion
noncomputable def codRestrict (f : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) {A : L.Substructure N} (h : A â‰¤ f.target) :
```
You will need to lowerCamelCase this as well, but just wondering: where is that name coming from? What's the `PartialEquiv` analogue? I couldn't find it quickly.

This could be thought of as an analog of `PartialEquiv.toEquiv` composed with `FirstOrder.Language.Substructure.topEquiv`.

The design for this should be consistent with whatever kind of `toEmbedding` we want. The maximalist idea would be to define
`FirstOrder.Language.PartialEquiv.toEmbedding` and
`FirstOrder.Language.PartialEquiv.toEquiv`
which involve substructures as domains (and in the case of the equiv, codomain), and then to also define versions that go between the original structures, taking in `= âŠ¤` equations. These would be implemented by composing the substructure version with `FirstOrder.Language.Substructure.topEquiv`.
I've made an attempt to clean up this bit of API - I think it's ready for review.

Can't this be generalised to something like
```suggestion
noncomputable def map (f : M â†ª[L] O) (g : N â†ª[L] P) (e : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] N) : O â‰ƒâ‚š[L] P where
```
? If so, then probably we instead want two definitions: one for composing by an embedding on the left and another one for composing by an embedding on the right

```suggestion
theorem map_comp_comm (f : M â†ª[L] N) (g : M â‰ƒâ‚š[L] M) :
```
or something like that? We don't use `commutes` anywhere else, only `comm`

Ah! Your `PartialEquiv.map` is like `Embedding.toPartialEquiv f \comp g \comp (Embedding.toPartialEquiv f).symm`.

Do you think you could *define* it like that? /maybe not define it at all

At the moment, there's no notion of composition at all for `PartialEquiv` - in general, it should give you a partial equiv whose domains are intersections of the domains of things being composed, and that might get slightly slippery.
It does make sense what it should be for composing on the left or the right with an embedding. If one of those is defined, the other can be defined using `symm` a few times.

In any event, I'm going to go poke around with the PRs depending on this one to see how much they use this specific formulation of `map`.
Yeah, I would potentially suggest removing `map` from this PR and move to a later PR which needs it. Then we'll have a better idea of what exactly we want from it.
It looks like it's only needed for preliminary work that was done on showing existence of FraÃ¯ssÃ© limits, and not for uniqueness, so I'm happy to trim it for now to get the PR through.
I'll let you do that before my next review
